</p>
<p>July</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">young man who made me signs to follow him to his hut.  This I did and found a mat spread upon which I was desired to take my seat<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  He then presented me with a dish full of water of which I drank that Dish was then removed and replaced by a nother containing a quantity of small balls composed of a mixture of berries dried meat &amp; parched corn pounded together in a mortar<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Having <span class="DelHand-author">e</span>at<span class="AddHand-author">e</span> of this dish he brought back the water then lighted his pipe with some of his own tobacco which is a poor substitute for the real sort and has a nauseous unpleasant smell.  After Emptying his pipe he brought me a Buffaloe Robe which he wished to trade for ammunition this I declined gave him a piece of Tobacco and returned to my hut.  Soon after this we took a<span class="AddHand-author"> walk to</span> the burying ground situated upon the declivity of a high hill.  Here we saw many unpleasant spectacles of decayed and decaying human frames many t<span class="AddHand-author">u</span>mbling to the ground through age whilst others by their stench obliged us to keep to the windward<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  We also observed a great pile of human bones which as we</p>
